<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1925-12-06T21:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1925-12-06T21:00:00-05:00" n="452" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d452">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/6825: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1925-12-07T10:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">December 7,
                                        1925—10 a.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received December 7—3:04
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>517. My 514, December 4, 1 p.m.<note n="38" xml:id="d452fn38">Not
                                printed.</note> Following from American consul, Mukden: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“December 6, 11 a.m. Chang has suffered complete debacle. Young
                                    Chang retreated to a place very near to Mukden; position of
                                    Chang absolutely hopeless. There is a general exodus from the
                                    city. I do not expect any danger to any foreigners. Have heard
                                    Marshal will leave today.”</p>
                            </quote></p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">MacMurray</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>